% v2-final abstract. n=100 numbers landed and INVERTED the smoke
% finding: pull (agent-as-reader) dominates intercept (framework-
% as-reader) on Pass^k with sign-test p=0.004, Cliff's δ=+0.18.
% Headline pivots to the pull-channel-generalization story.

Modern multi-agent LLM runtimes expose framework-level tool-call
interception as a production primitive: Strands' before/after
tool-call hooks~\cite{strandshooks2025}, Amazon Bedrock AgentCore
Policy~\cite{agentcorepolicy2025}, LangChain middleware's
\texttt{wrap\_tool\_call}~\cite{langchainmiddleware2026}, and
Microsoft Agent Framework's function
middleware~\cite{msagentframework2026} all let the framework
inspect, rewrite, or block a tool call's arguments and result
without modifying the agent's tool schema or prompt.  These
mechanisms are deployed today for blocking, validation, retries,
and caching, and the industry trend points toward more framework
mediation.  In parallel, recent work proposes MCP-conformant shared
stores as a coordination substrate
(CA-MCP~\cite{camcp2026}, Terrarium~\cite{terrarium2025},
MPAC~\cite{mpac2026}) but routes coordination data through
agent-visible store-query tools or server-to-server channels.
Whether the \emph{architectural} choice of reader-side path---agent
vs.\ framework---moves a benchmark needle, holding the underlying
coordination store constant, has not been measured.

We answer that question and report a counter-intuitive result.  We
introduce \textbf{ET-MCP}, a task-scoped trace store of typed events
biased toward negative knowledge (failed paths, constraint
violations, failed-trial actions) conformant with the MCP 2026-07-28
specification, and instantiate two reader-side architectures over
the same store: a \emph{pull} interface where the agent receives a
curated peer-warnings summary at trial start, and an
\emph{intercept} layer where the orchestrator prepends a
\texttt{[PEER-WARNING]} block to a tool's \emph{response} when the
call's (name, arguments) match a peer event from a prior failed
trial of the same task.  Pull and intercept share the event store,
the writer policy, the event taxonomy, and the MCP transport; they
differ only in who is the active reader.  This is, to our
knowledge, the first controlled head-to-head comparison of
reader-side coordination architectures under matched payload.

We evaluate on $\tau^2$-bench retail~\cite{tau2bench2025} at
$n{=}100$ tasks (600 trials, Claude Haiku~4.5, paired by task).
\emph{Pull reaches pass$^1$=0.62 and pass$^2$=0.44; intercept reaches
pass$^1$=0.44 and pass$^2$=0.33; no-coordination reaches
pass$^1$=0.54 and pass$^2$=0.38.}  Pull beats no-coordination by
$+8$\,pp on pass$^1$ and $+6$\,pp on pass$^2$ (Cliff's
$\delta$=$+0.08$ and $+0.06$ respectively); intercept underperforms
no-coordination by $-10$\,pp and $-5$\,pp.  Most importantly,
\textbf{pull significantly dominates intercept under matched
payload}: 27 task-level losses for intercept against 9 wins on
pass$^1$ (paired sign test $p{=}0.004$, Cliff's $\delta$=$+0.18$),
and 18-vs-7 on pass$^2$ ($p{=}0.043$).  At comparable input-token
cost, the agent-side reader is the architecturally superior
choice---counter to the production-stack trend toward framework-
mediated coordination.  The mechanistic intuition: intercept fires
on every matching tool call (mean 2.8 events per intercept trial,
up to 8), blasting the agent with warnings on calls that may have
legitimately succeeded in some past trial; pull lets the agent read
one curated summary at trial start and exercise judgment.  Agent
selectivity, not framework mediation, carries the architectural
win.

A within-system ablation factorial on TravelPlanner (810 trials,
nine conditions) corroborates the mechanism: holding the
negative-knowledge payload constant, the pull channel
architecturally outperforms structured push baselines
($3.9\%$ vs.\ $5.2\%$ redundancy, Wilcoxon-significant
$p{<}0.05$), and the no-query bound and ranker-randomization
ablation triangulate the same conclusion.  The within-system
finding now generalizes to a Sierra-published peer-reviewed
benchmark with cross-protocol significance.

We additionally release a $\sim$700-line Anthropic-native
$\tau^2$-bench harness that mitigates a documented bug class in
$\tau^2$-bench's bundled litellm-based pipeline---malformed
Anthropic-API message histories producing $\geq30\%$ silent infra
errors on multi-turn dual-control retail tasks, consistent with
multiple open issues in BerriAI's
\texttt{litellm}~\cite{litellmissue12404,litellmissue15322}.
Zero infra errors at 600 trials.  We position this as
post-deployment trustworthiness infrastructure for groups
evaluating Anthropic deployments on the $\tau$-bench family.

The headline claim is methodological and architectural: in
tool-using multi-agent systems, the reader-side path matters more
than the coordination payload, and the agent-side reader path
significantly outperforms the framework-side reader path on a
public benchmark under matched payload---suggesting that selective
agent-mediated reading, not blind framework-side injection, is the
deployable coordination architecture.
